### One structural call I left for you

This is the only thing above a cohesion pass's pay grade, so I'm flagging rather than acting:

**"Why Sadie Sink Runs on Self-Doubt" (H2-3) overlaps the diagnosis section.** Both run doubt-as-fuel on the same Harper's Bazaar quotes. The section *does* earn part of its keep — the doubt=love/caring equation and "even joy passes inspection" are new — but a reader hitting a fourth restatement of the doubt thesis (intro → TL;DR → diagnosis → this) may feel it as repetition rather than deepening. Your fresh-eyes note caught the same thing. **Options:** (a) leave it — the caring angle justifies it; (b) tighten H2-3 to *only* the caring/love beat and the theater-return, cutting anything that re-proves "doubt = fuel," which the diagnosis already nailed. I'd lean (b) as a light trim, but it's a substance call, not a cohesion one, so it's yours.

The through-line itself is solid — the piece opens on "am I actually good at this?" and closes on "still not sure she is any good at it," and the doubt→protection arc lands cleanly. It's ship-cohesive as-is.
